import javax.crypto.*;   // For AES, you need this library which implements Cryptography Standard (Cipher) Interface in Java Security package by Sun Microsystem Inc . It includes classes like DES ,DESede and Advanced Encryption标准(AES). Also provides implementations for symmetric key algorithms such as Blowfish.
import java.security.*;  // This class java_52674_CredentialValidator_A07 used to create a new KeyProvider, GenerateKeyPairGenerator instances of the specified algorithm (like RSA), Signature instance by using keys or MessageDigest and Cipher respectively... etc .  
import javax.crypto.spec.*;  // For symmetric algorithms like AES you need this library which provides classes for encryption/decryption operations on a block's worth data, also has methods to encrypt given plain text into cipher-text (encrypted) or decode encrypted output back in the form of original unreadable message.
  
public class Main {  // The main method starts execution from here by default . It will call all other non static and public functions inside this Class if its name is 'Main' as per Java Convention for starting a program/application via command line (main function).    Crypto library in java only provides basic cryptography services.
     private Key key;  // This represents the secret password which we will use to encryt our data and decryption of encrypted text back into plaintext . It's used for symmetric encryption using AES algorithm via javax package from Java Security class..   Here, a new instance (key) is created.
     private Cipher cipher;  // This represents the actual block-based stream that we use to encrypt and decryption our data in real world scenario . It's used for symmetric encryption using AES algorithm via javax package from Java Security class..   Here, a new instance (cipher) is created.
     public static void main(String[] args){  // This method will run when the program starts up , where all prerequisites are prepared before starting . So we have to call these functions in our code either by using 'new' or calling it from an object of this class..   Here, a new instance (Main) is created.
        try {  //try block here will contain the operation that may throw checked exception such as InvalidKeyException... etc and catch block would handle those exceptions if any occur in runtime then program execution gets handled by catching blocks . Try/Catch mechanism helps to write robust code which can face errors at run time , so not all possibilities are covered there.
             // Here we will create a new key, cipher & specify operation for encryption or decryption  using the Key and Cipher in crypto provider class..   For example: generateKey is used to creating an RSA Keys which can be further encrypted then encrypting that data with our newly created/generating keys.
             //And same goes on Decription of Encrypted Data . Please note we need Java 6 or above version for the code snippet and also make sure you have installed Bouncy Castle java crypto library in your project, which includes AES encryption support using BC's provider classes..   For example: KeyGenerator , SecretKey generate & encrypt a message...
            } catch (Exception e) {  //catch block will handle exceptions. In this case we are handling Invalid key exception . Here you can provide more specific details about the problem that is occurring and where to look for it, in most cases when working with encrypted data or decrypted text ..   For example: if a user tries encrypt/decryption using wrong type of keys then how should program handle this ?
        }  // end try block. If anything fails inside catch blocks we want the system fail gracefully and not stop because it's an unhandled exception, hence use 'throw new Exception(..);'. This means that even if something goes as expected within a function (try/catch), then when such error occurred in outside of this code block or called method than JVM will consider catch is part of the same statement and stop execution right there.
        // end finally: In case any exception occurs, it's not guaranteed whether that particular try-finally segment executes because if you put an unhandled Exception inside a Try/Catch Block then even within this block all code after will be executed under catch condition which is fine but we can use the Finally to ensure some cleanup work.
     }  // end main method and ends here..   If any changes are made in 'main' function it must have full line indentation otherwise java won’t recognize our statements inside this block as part of that particular statement, Hence make sure you follow proper coding standards for Java ie: Full-fledged code should be properly structured.
}  // end Main Class and ends here..   If any changes are made in 'Main' class it must have full line indentation otherwise java won’t recognize our statements inside this block as part of that particular statement, Hence make sure you follow proper coding standards for Java ie: Full-fledged code should be properly structured.